org.apache.freemarker.core

Class NonTemplateCallPlace

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.apache.freemarker.core.NonTemplateCallPlace
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    CallPlace

    public final class NonTemplateCallPlace
extends Object
implements CallPlace
    CallPlace used when a TemplateDirectiveModel is called from outside a template (such as from user Java code).

      • NonTemplateCallPlace

        public NonTemplateCallPlace(int firstTargetJavaParameterTypeIndex,
                            Class<?>[] targetJavaParameterTypes)
        Parameters:
        firstTargetJavaParameterTypeIndex - See CallPlace.getFirstTargetJavaParameterTypeIndex()
        targetJavaParameterTypes - The target Java types of the arguments of the invocation, starting with the target Java type of the argument at index firstTargetJavaParameterTypeIndex, and usually ending with the target type of the last argument that has a non-null target type (although having null-s at the end is legal too). For example, using Java-like call syntax, if the call is like m(a, b, (Foo) c, d, (Bar) e, f), then firstTargetJavaParameterTypeIndex is 2, and the array will be new Class<?>[] { } [ Foo.class, null, Bar.class ].

      • executeNestedContent

        public void executeNestedContent(TemplateModel[] nestedContentArgs,
                                 Writer out,
                                 Environment env)
                          throws TemplateException,
                                 IOException
        Does nothing.
        Specified by:
        executeNestedContent in interface CallPlace
        Parameters:
        nestedContentArgs - The nested content parameter values to pass to the nested content (as in <@foo bar; i, j>${i}, ${j}</@foo> there are 2 such parameters, whose value you set here), or null if there's none. This array must be CallPlace.getNestedContentParameterCount() long, or else FreeMarker will throw an TemplateException with a descriptive error message that tells to user that they need to declare that many nested content parameters as the length of this array. If you want to allow the caller to not declare some of the nested content parameters, then you have to make this array shorter according to CallPlace.getNestedContentParameterCount().
        Throws:
        TemplateException
        IOException

      • getOrCreateCustomData

        public Object getOrCreateCustomData(Object providerIdentity,
                                    CommonSupplier<?> supplier)
                             throws CallPlaceCustomDataInitializationException
        Always throws UnsupportedOperationException.
        Specified by:
        getOrCreateCustomData in interface CallPlace
        Parameters:
        providerIdentity - This is usually the class of the TemplateDirectiveModel that creates (and uses) the custom data, or if you are using your own class for the custom data object (as opposed to a class from some more generic API), then that class. This is needed as the same call place might calls different directives depending on runtime conditions, and so it must be ensured that these directives won't accidentally read each other's custom data, ending up with class cast exceptions or worse. In the current implementation, if there's a providerIdentity mismatch (means, the providerIdentity object used when the custom data was last set isn't the exactly same object as the one provided with the parameter now), the previous custom data will be just ignored as if it was null. So if multiple directives that use the custom data feature use the same call place, the caching of the custom data can be inefficient, as they will keep overwriting each other's custom data. (In a more generic implementation the providerIdentity would be a key in a IdentityHashMap, but then this feature would be slower, while providerIdentity mismatches aren't occurring in most applications.)
        supplier - Called when the custom data wasn't yet set, to invoke its initial value. If this parameter is null and the custom data wasn't set yet, then null will be returned. The returned value of CommonSupplier.get() can be any kind of object, but can't be null.
        Returns:
        The current custom data object, or possibly null if there was no CommonSupplier provided.
        Throws:
        CallPlaceCustomDataInitializationException - If the CommonSupplier had to be invoked but failed.
